nodes.title: Note: Raw latent version
widgets_values:
Since the **TextEncodeQwenImageEditPlus** node will scale the image to 1M pixels, you might find that the output has a pixel-shifting issue.

The **Raw latent version** is to provide the raw latent to the sampler. This is the way you can provide the raw latent as an input condition.

nodes.title: Character Fusion Prompt
widgets_values:
Here's the prompt structure, you can try improving on it if you like:

Make the lighting of [the subject] to match the lighting of the scene. [The subject] is [lit in a certain way] and [casts a shadow and/or a reflection a certain way onto some surface]. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of [the subject].

Feel free to adjust as needed!

nodes.title: Color Match
widgets_values:
There is a 'Color Match' Node (Cyan) in the comp section, it tints the color of the fusion image back to match the original background image. 

It must not be bypassed, but you can adjust the strength, and, if need be, disable it by making the strength '0'. Higher for real/3d, lower for anime/cartoon.

By default I've set it to 20.

nodes.title: Character Image
widgets_values:
For best results, the character should be fully within the image, forward or side facing and not upside-down. Sitting is generally fine, lying down is more complicated, especially if lying on one's chest.

If the camera angle is too extreme, probability of failure is higher. Even if it succeeds in capturing the character, that extreme camera angle is now baked into the pose, posing problems later on with fusion.

There is no limit on style, nor expression, nor body type. The lora will try to capture it all, and generally does a good job.

For best results you can gen both the Character Pose ang Character Sheet image with the same style.

nodes.title: Dummy Crop Edge Reserve Percentage
widgets_values:
This controls the extra white space around the generated Character Dummy. It should be small, but not 0. 

I've set it to 5% and I don't think it needs changing.

nodes.title: Character positioning / scale / rotation
widgets_values:
Use the red "ImageBlendAdvance" node in Preprocessing to position, scale and rotate the character.

x and y percent determines the position of the character on the background. 'scale' and 'rotation' are self-explanatory.

Performance is best IF character is standing or directly in contact with the scene, with scale, position, and rotation that makes sense.

nodes.title: Scene Image
widgets_values:
The scene to place the character in.

There should be nothing in the foreground obscuring the character.

See above for Character Dummy placement in scene.

nodes.title: Upscaling
widgets_values:
Use your upscaler of choice.

If your character is only going to be on a small portion of your background, its recommended that you upscale your background enough so that the cropped image is at least 1 megapixel in size.

I'm using the following:

2x Manga Ora for anime characters.

2xLiveActionV1_Span_4900 for live action and 3dcg.

4x remacri for scenes or live action and 3dcg
Without changing the pose, remove the person's hair, clothing and accessories, and make them completely naked. Make the skin white and the background white.

nodes.title: Edge Mask Adjustments
widgets_values:
If your character or shadow are completely contained and within the edge mask, then the LayerMaskTransform, blue node, in Compositing, can be bypassed entirely. This is the default setting. When bypassed, all four edges will be feathered. Should be fine even if it remains on, although the bottom edge seam may be visible.

If your character or shadow contacts the edge of the full image, then the LayerMaskTransform must be activated. When active, the default option is is that the BOTTOM edge of the mask is not feathered. I did this because the character clipping into the bottom edge seemed like the most common form of clipping.

If your character or shadow contacts one of the side edges as well, you can further adjust manually with '1' in X Scale and either '1' (for leftward) or '-1' (for rightward) in X Move.

This setup only supports clipping one edge in each x and y direction. Anything more complicated than that and you'll need to disconnect all non-mask connections in LayerMaskTransform, calculate and enter the values manually. You can  use the expanded math node results as reference numbers to work off of.

nodes.title: HOLD THE CHEESE!
widgets_values:
This workflow is BEEEG!

How do I use this easily?

Here's how!

Download all the models, put them in the right folders, hit ctrl+R to refresh, then load them into each model loader (magenta nodes).

Load a Character Sheet, Character Pose and Scene images. (red nodes)

Edit the lighting portion in the Character Fusion prompt (green node)

For the best experience, use a Pose image where the entire character in is the image, and a Character Sheet generated with my [Lazy Character Sheet](https://civitai.com/models/2078957?modelVersionId=2352325) workflow.

nodes.title: Character Dummy Prompt
widgets_values: This prompt does not need to be changed.

nodes.title: Workflow Seed Control
widgets_values:
In order to avoid using a switch or manually bypassing chunks of the workflow, I'm just gonna use seeds to control the different parts. 

Setting a seed to 'fixed' will make that part 'fixed' and not run if it's already run once before. 'randomize' or the other two settings will make it 'run'.

Caveats as follows:

Character Dummy seed 'fixed' will prevent it from running after one run. Can be either.

Dummy Enhancement seed 'fixed' will prevent it from running after one run if previous step is also 'fixed'. This can remain 'fixed' as long as you're satisfied with its enhancement of the original Dummy image.

Character Fusion seed 'fixed will prevent it from running after one run if previous 2 steps have already run.

nodes.title: How to use a separate Character Dummy image
widgets_values:
If the internal Character Dummy + Enhancement groups yield mediocre results, and you want to use an external Character Dummy image, here's how:

Load your external Character Dummy image (orange node)

Connect the Orange Character Dummy (Optional) Node to the nearby orange upscale node.

In order to undo this, you need to connect the orange VAE decode node (bottom right group) to the orange upscale node (three columns to the right)

The external Character Dummy node can be whatever as long as its a character that's bald naked line art and/or white 3d rendering.

Another possibility is that you want to run the Character Dummy portion, take the final output and do manual touch-up in important parts, like with the hands and face, then continue using that image. This modification will allow you to do that!

nodes.title: Character sheet
widgets_values:
The character sheet can be generated using my Lazy Character Sheet workflow.

The character should be facing front, left, back and right, in that order.

The charaBG lora can run if its just the front image, or just the front torso image. In some cases, these types of images work better. Test and see what works best.

nodes.title: Dummy Enhancement Prompt
widgets_values:
Its best you describe briefly the bottom portion of the image. Mention the style and sex of the character if possible.

For example:

"This is a anime line art picture of a white model of a muscular bald woman."

"This is a picture of a 3d model of a middle-aged bald man."

Enhance image quality. Maintain color, style and detail.

This is an anime line art picture of a white model of a muscular bald woman.

Change the character in the background and pose pucture1 to a character on pictuer2. Make the lighting of the woman to match the lighting of the scene. She is rimlit from above with cool blue moonlight. She is lit from behind with a soft red light. She casts a soft shadow on the ground. Maintain color, lighting and mood in the scene. Maintain the pose and details of the woman.

nodes.title: Crop Edge Reserve Percentage
widgets_values:
Crop Edge Reserve Percentage:
The amount to extend the character's crop by mask. The default is 15%.

If your character takes up a smaller amount of the cropped image or if you're getting weird residual characters, you need to reduce this value. The character body and head must take up a significant portion of the cropped image.
